 \section{A Call for Contribution}
-The rapid growth of the skills ecosystem—from a handful of curated packages to over 400,000 public Skills in a matter of months—signals genuine demand. Yet the infrastructure needed to make this ecosystem reliable, safe, and sustainable does not yet exist. We believe that if the research community addresses the open questions outlined in Section 4, the impact on AI agents will unfold across two horizons.
-In the near term, agents equipped with high-quality, composable \emph{skills} will achieve reliable expert-level execution in specialized domains that raw model scaling cannot reach: a clinical agent that follows verified diagnostic workflows rather than hallucinating procedures, a synthesis planning agent that executes feasible chemical routes rather than plausible-sounding ones, a financial agent that applies precise domain logic rather than approximate reasoning. The gains come not from a larger model, but from procedural expertise loaded on demand.
+The rapid growth of the skills ecosystem—from a handful of curated packages to over 400,000 public Skills in months—signals genuine demand, yet the infrastructure to make it reliable, safe, and sustainable does not yet exist. If the community addresses the open questions in Section 4, the impact will unfold across two horizons.
+In the near term, \emph{skills} let agents reach expert-level execution that raw scaling cannot: a clinical agent that follows verified diagnostic workflows rather than hallucinating procedures, a synthesis agent that executes feasible chemical routes rather than plausible-sounding ones, a financial agent that applies precise domain logic rather than approximate reasoning—gains that come not from a larger model but from procedural expertise loaded on demand.
 
-In the longer term, the \emph{skills} paradigm opens a more ambitious possibility: agents that do not merely consume \emph{skills}, but create, evaluate, and evolve them~\cite{skillrl2026,yang2026autoskill}. An agent that completes a complex task can distill that experience into a reusable \emph{skill}; an agent that observes \emph{skill} failures can revise the procedure; a community of agents can collectively improve a shared \emph{skill} library over time. This self-evolving loop—where agents become both users and authors of procedural knowledge—represents a qualitative shift from static tool use toward a living, self-improving knowledge infrastructure. 
+In the longer term, the paradigm opens an ambitious possibility: agents that not only consume \emph{skills} but create, evaluate, and evolve them~\cite{skillrl2026,yang2026autoskill}—distilling completed tasks into reusable \emph{skills}, revising procedures after failures, and collectively improving a shared library. This self-evolving loop, where agents become both users and authors of procedural knowledge, marks a shift from static tool use toward a living, self-improving knowledge infrastructure.
 
 Realizing either horizon requires foundational research that the community has not yet undertaken. We therefore outline a call for contribution from three complementary perspectives.
 
 \vspace{-0.05in}
-\paragraph{\textbf{The Skill developer's perspective}} The ask is straightforward: follow emerging standards when authoring \emph{skills}, and share them openly. A \emph{skill} that is well-scoped, clearly documented, and contributed to a public registry does not just help one agent;  it becomes reusable infrastructure for many agents that follows. The more developers treat \emph{skills} as a \textbf{shared knowledge commons} rather than isolated proprietary artifacts, the more quickly the ecosystem can accumulate value.
+\paragraph{\textbf{The Skill developer's perspective}} The ask is simple: follow emerging standards and share \emph{skills} openly. A well-scoped, clearly documented \emph{skill} in a public registry does not just help one agent; it becomes reusable infrastructure for many. The more developers treat \emph{skills} as a \textbf{shared knowledge commons} rather than proprietary artifacts, the faster the ecosystem accumulates value.
 
 \vspace{-0.05in}
 \paragraph{\textbf{The Skill user's perspective}} 
-The ask is to treat \emph{skills} as a first-class mechanism for extending agent capability, learn how to select and compose them effectively, and provide feedback when they fail. When a user reports that a \emph{skill} behaves unexpectedly, interferes with adjacent tasks, or breaks under certain conditions, that feedback improves not just one interaction but the reliability of the broader ecosystem.
